#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:1
msgid "The Carpentries Style Guide"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:3
msgid ""
"This guide aims to provide a standard reference point when questions "
"arise about style for The Carpentries - how we would prefer people to "
"reference us, how best to render dates and times for a global community, "
"when to use what capitalisation, and other questions of style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:5
msgid ""
"We will adhere to a similar style  on our website and in other material "
"we make widely available such as blog posts, but not necessarily in "
"lessons. To ensure that the style guide is as widely applicable as "
"possible, UK English spellings and usage will be used in favour of "
"American spelling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:7
msgid ""
"The guide is a work in progress and additions are welcome. This version, "
"compiled by Belinda Weaver, is a first draft."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:9
msgid ""
"Please note, as outlined in section C: The Carpentries, while sounding "
"plural, is a singular entity. Therefore, when referring to The "
"Carpentries, verbs should also be singular, e.g., ‘The Carpentries is …’."
" The full and correct title for the merged organization is The "
"Carpentries. However, terminology such as ‘A Carpentries workshop …’ is "
"acceptable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:13
msgid "A"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:15
msgid "abbreviations and acronyms"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:16
msgid ""
"Generally use all capitals for initialisms, e.g., NSF, CEO, BIDS. When "
"writing about an organisation or event within text, provide the acronym "
"in brackets on first use, and use the acronym to refer to the "
"organisation or event from then on. For example, ‘She was the chair of "
"the National Science Foundation (NSF) ... The NSF … ’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:18
msgid ""
"If an organisation is mentioned only once within a piece of text, say, in"
" a blog post, it is not necessary to provide its acronym. Do not use "
"acronyms without spelling these out first as country-specific acronym may"
" be unfamiliar to members of our community."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:20
msgid "accents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:22
msgid ""
"Use on non-English words when known. People’s names, in whatever "
"language, should also be given appropriate accents where known, e.g., "
"‘Arsène Lupin was a jewel thief who never got to Bogotá or Angoulême.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:24
msgid "adverbs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:26
msgid ""
"Hyphens are not needed after adverbs ending in -ly, e.g. a hotly argued "
"topic, a constantly evolving career, a recently published program, etc. "
"Hyphens are needed with short and common adverbs, e.g., ever-faithful "
"follower, ill-written script, much-quoted speech."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:28
msgid "ampersand"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:30
msgid ""
"In text and blog posts, use the ampersand in organisations’ names when "
"the organisation does so, e.g., P&O, AT&T."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:32
msgid "apostrophes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:34
msgid ""
"Indicates either a missing letter or letters (can’t, we’d, hadn’t) or a "
"possessive (Siobhan’s script). The correct use of the apostrophe is "
"important, as a misplacement or omission can alter a sentence’s meaning. "
"Apostrophes are not needed in dates. Preferred form is 1990s, not 1990’s;"
" the 70s, not the 70’s."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:38
msgid "B"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:40
msgid "bullet points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:42
msgid ""
"Should ideally include a full stop after each one if it is not just a "
"list of terms, i.e: <br>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:43
msgid "This is the first bullet point that covers a range of ideas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:44
msgid "This is the second that also ranges quite widely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:45
msgid "And this is the third and these are just examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:47
msgid "But <br>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:48
msgid "Instructors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:49
msgid "Trainers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:50
msgid "Mentors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:54
msgid "C"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:56
msgid "capital letters and capitalisation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:58
msgid ""
"titles<br> Render these with initial capitals, e.g., President Abraham "
"Lincoln, Facebook’s CEO, Pope John Paul II, the Secretary-General Ban-Ki "
"Moon."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:61
msgid ""
"government departments initial capitals, e.g., Department of Industry, "
"Department of Health. Use lower case when not referring to a department "
"by its proper name, e.g., ‘Senator Carr first led the Department of "
"Industry. The department is now led by … ’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:64
msgid ""
"government agencies, public bodies, quangos <br> Render these with "
"initial capitals, e.g., District Attorney’s Office, Human Rights "
"Commission, the University of Florida. Use lower case when not referring "
"to an organisation by its proper name, e.g., ‘She worked for the National"
" Society of Coders. The society was founded … ’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:67
msgid ""
"lesson titles and episode names <br> Lesson titles and episodes within "
"lessons should be rendered in Title case, i.e. all major words "
"capitalised, e.g., Introduction to Data; Project Organization and "
"Management for Genomics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:70
msgid ""
"names of institutions <br> Render these with initial capitals, e.g., "
"Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, Smithsonian Institute, the United "
"Nations, the European Union."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:73
msgid ""
"roles <br> Roles within The Carpentries are always capitalised. Therefore"
" we use Instructor, Trainer, Maintainer, Mentor, and Curriculum Advisor. "
"Helper and host are not capitalised as these are not official roles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:78
msgid "Carpentries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:80
msgid ""
"The Carpentries, while sounding plural, is a singular entity. Therefore, "
"when referring to The Carpentries, verbs should also be singular, e.g., "
"‘The Carpentries is …’. The full and correct title for the merged "
"organization is The Carpentries. However, terminology such as ‘A "
"Carpentries workshop …’ is acceptable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:82
msgid "commas"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:83
msgid ""
"Use commas to separate clauses in long sentences. ‘If the judges truly "
"reflected on their decisions regarding the non-award of prizes in 2010, "
"they would not find it hard to see why people objected to their choices.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:85
msgid ""
"Commas can be used definitively. For example, in this sentence: ‘The "
"developer, Sue Miller, is a keen coder,’ the use of commas indicates that"
" there is only one developer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:87
msgid ""
"Where no such definition is needed, e.g., ‘PyCon speaker Mary Clough won "
"the award,’ no commas are needed since there are many speakers at PyCon, "
"not just one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:89
msgid ""
"A comma is also crucial to avoid ambiguity in examples such as this: ‘The"
" report criticises the judges who have been accused of favouritism.’ A "
"comma after ‘judges’ would have made it clear that all judges have been "
"accused of favouritism. Without the comma, the sentence implies that only"
" some judges have been criticised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:91
msgid "See also Oxford comma."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:93
msgid "company names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:94
msgid ""
"Company names are always singular, e.g., ‘Twitter is …’, ‘Amazon Web "
"Services is …’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:98
msgid "D"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:100
msgid "dates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:101
msgid "Our style is 21 July, 2011 (day month year)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:103
msgid "Other renderings: ‘In the 21st century’ but ‘21st-century science’."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:106
msgid ""
"Use figures for decades, e.g., the 1990s, the radical 60s, etc. Do not "
"add an apostrophe to decades, i.e. 1990s, not 1990’s; the 70s, not the "
"70’s."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:108
msgid "See also times.<br> See also seasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:113
msgid "E"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:115
msgid "e.g."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:116
msgid ""
"include full stops, and always follow with a comma, whether you are using"
" the abbreviated form, e.g., or the written-out version, for example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:118
msgid "etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:119
msgid "Include final full stop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:123
msgid "F"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:125
msgid "figures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:126
#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:175
msgid ""
"Always spell out in writing the numbers from one to nine. Use numerals "
"for numbers 10 to 999,999, and thereafter go back to writing numbers out "
"in full, e.g., one million readers, eight billion people, but when the "
"first number is above nine, you can go back to figures for that first "
"part, e.g., 20 million lines. Spell out ordinals from the first to the "
"ninth, e.g., third, fifth, and thereafter use 10th, 31st, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:128
msgid "first name, forename, given name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:129
msgid ""
"These terms to be used in preference to the term ‘Christian name’, which "
"might offend non-Christians. Use first names the first time someone is "
"mentioned, but not subsequently, e.g., ‘Mary Brown came late to "
"programming ... Brown later went on to develop several well-known "
"programs.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:131
msgid ""
"Avoid using initials rather than a name, unless that is how a person is "
"best known, e.g., J. K. Galbraith."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:133
msgid "foreign accents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:134
msgid ""
"If possible, use the correct accents on people’s names in any language, "
"e.g., Sven-Göran Eriksson (Swedish), Béla Bartók (Hungarian), Phượng "
"Nguyễn (Vietnamese)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:136
msgid "foreign names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:137
msgid ""
"The French (or French origin) de, d’, des, la, les or le and the Dutch "
"van are normally lowercase when the name is fully written out, e.g., "
"Marianne d’Alpuget, Erik van der Walden, but capitalised when written "
"without forenames, e.g., D’Alpuget, Van der Walden."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:139
msgid "foreign words and phrases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:140
msgid ""
"Italicise these and provide accents where applicable, e.g., bête noire. "
"In the case of frequently used foreign terms in accepted English usage, "
"e.g., avant garde, vis a vis, vice versa, you do not need to italicise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:142
msgid "fractions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:143
msgid ""
"Render as two-thirds, three-quarters, etc., but two and a half needs no "
"hyphens.<br> See also figures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:148
msgid "H"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:150
msgid "honorifics and titles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:151
msgid ""
"Honorifics which denote occupations, e.g., Doctor, Professor, can "
"initially be used within text or in blog posts. Drop honorifics and first"
" names after the first mention and use surname only from then on, e.g., "
"‘Professor Gillian Kramer teaches … Kramer has spent a lot of time...’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:153
msgid "Honorifics such as FRCS should not include full stops."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:155
msgid "I"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:156
msgid "initials"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:157
msgid ""
"Separate initials in names from each other with spaces and full stops, "
"e.g., J. K. Galbraith."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:159
msgid "-isation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:160
msgid "not –ization, e.g., organisation, characterisation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:162
msgid "-ise"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:163
msgid ""
"not -ize at end of word, e.g., characterise, sympathise, organise. One "
"exception is capsize."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:165
msgid "italics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:166
msgid ""
"Foreign words and phrases, and scientific names, e.g., Macropus rufus, "
"Bufo marinus."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:168
msgid "N"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:170
msgid "names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:171
msgid ""
"Do not use the terms Christian name, first name, or forename. Instead use"
" given name or personal name. We will defer to people's chosen spelling, "
"choice of given name, punctuation, capitalisation, and name order (when "
"known or obtainable).<br> See also foreign names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:174
msgid "numbers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:177
msgid ""
"When starting a sentence with any number, the number should be written "
"out as words, e.g., ‘Twenty-five people attended the workshop.’ "
"‘Nineteen-ninety-five was not a leap year.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:179
msgid "O"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:181
msgid "Oxford comma"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:182
msgid ""
"A comma before the final ‘and’ in lists. Straightforward lists (he wrote "
"books, short stories and poetry) do not need the extra comma, but "
"sometimes it can help the reader to know which bits go together, e.g., "
"‘she wrote in these genres – horror, mystery, cloak and dagger, and "
"fantasy’, and sometimes it is essential for clarity and meaning, e.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:184
msgid ""
"I spoke to my sisters, Olga Petrova, and Susanne De Vries (means I spoke "
"to my sisters AND to Olga Petrova and Susanne De Vries)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:186
msgid ""
"I spoke to my sisters, Olga Petrova and Susanne De Vries (this wrongly "
"implies that Olga Petrova and Susanne De Vries are the sisters in "
"question.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:188
msgid "Carpentries style is to use the Oxford comma."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:190
msgid "P"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:191
msgid "per cent"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:192
msgid ""
"Please spell this out in text, e.g., not as %, and write as two words, "
"not one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:194
msgid "Q"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:196
msgid "quotation marks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:198
msgid ""
"Use single quotes at the start and end of a quoted section, with double "
"quotes for quoted words within that section. Place full stops and commas "
"inside the quotes for a complete quoted sentence; otherwise the full stop"
" comes outside, e.g.,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:200
msgid ""
"‘Anna said: “Your style guide needs updating,” and I said: “I agree.”’ "
"‘Anna said updating the guide was “a difficult and time-consuming task”.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:203
msgid ""
"For parentheses inside direct quotes, use square brackets, e.g., The "
"judges said, ‘We very much liked the work of Goran [Kovacs] from "
"Croatia’."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:205
msgid "quotations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:206
msgid ""
"Colons, rather than commas, should be used to introduce quotations from "
"speeches or writings that run longer than a single sentence, e.g., Brown "
"said: ‘Winning the Nobel Prize was a highlight. It will change my life. I"
" can’t believe my luck.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:208
msgid ""
"To introduce phrases or single sentence quotations, a comma is "
"preferable, e.g., Brown said, ‘Winning the Nobel Prize was a highlight.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:210
msgid "R"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:212
msgid "roles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:213
msgid ""
"Roles within The Carpentries are always capitalised. Therefore we use "
"Instructor, Trainer, Maintainer, Mentor, and Curriculum Advisor. Helper "
"and host are not capitalised as these are not official roles."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:215
msgid "S"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:217
msgid "scientific names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:218
msgid ""
"Render these in italics, with the first name, which denotes genus, having"
" an initial capital, with the second, which denotes species, written in "
"lower case, e.g., Aedes aegypti (yellow fever mosquito), Crocodylus "
"porosus (Saltwater crocodile), Macropus rufus (Red kangaroo)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:220
msgid "seasons"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:221
msgid ""
"Avoid using seasons when discussing or announcing events, as seasons vary"
" from hemisphere to hemisphere. What is Fall in the USA is spring in "
"Australia. Use a month range instead, e.g., January to March, or use "
"halves or quarters, e.g., ‘This happened in the first quarter of 2018’, "
"‘This is planned for the second half of the year.’<br> See also dates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:224
msgid "singular or plural?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:225
msgid ""
"Corporate entities take the singular: e.g., ‘The NSF has announced … ’ In"
" subsequent references, use a singular pronoun: ‘It will cover the "
"Olympics.’ The Carpentries is always singular."
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:227
msgid "square brackets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:228
msgid ""
"In text, square brackets are used for interpolated words in quotations, "
"e.g., Olav Jonsson said, ‘Matthew [Brown] went to Capetown to address a "
"conference.’"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:230
msgid "T"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:232
msgid "times"
msgstr ""

#: ../../handbook/topic_folders/communications/style-guide.md:233
msgid ""
"Times should be rendered in UTC in a 24-hour format, e.g., 12:00 UTC, "
"17:30 UTC, 09:00 UTC. Do not use local zones, e.g., PDT, AEST. If you "
"want to make times meaningful for people in a range of time zones, use "
"the Event Time Announcer (using your UTC time and date as the basis to "
"create the event) to create a linkable time that will render locally for "
"each person who uses it, e.g., 20 August, 2018 22:00 UTC: "
"https://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/fixedtime.html?msg=Carpentries+Mentoring+Committee+Meeting+2&iso=20180820T22&p1=%3A&ah=1"
msgstr ""

